One would hope that the ordinary Reaſon of every Man that will make uſe of it, ſhould prevent his falling into ſuch groſs Imaginations, and ſuch childiſh Conceits as theſe Strains of Devotion do betray: But after our bleſſed Saviour diſcovered, more than once 
                           See Luc. ii. 49. Luc. viii. 21. John ii. 4. whilſt he was here upon Earth, That in Matters that related to the Exerciſe of his Office, when he was about his Fathers Buſineſs, the Interpoſing of Mother and Brethren was unſeaſonable and unacceptable, and rather repreſſed by him than incouraged; 
                           Chriſtus non agnoſcit viſcera humana, operaturus facta divina. S. Auguſtin. Tract. 8. in Johan. to think by theſe Conſiderations to move him in Heaven, ſeems to argue ſuch Men forſaken of Reaſon, and to have too little Regard to the Honour of God.
